 {"id":"bd-14c0","title":"join\! macro: concurrent execution with aggregated outcomes","description":"# join\! Macro Implementation

## Goal

Implement the join\! macro for running multiple futures concurrently and collecting all results.

## Semantics

```rust
// Basic usage
let (a, b, c) = join\!(fut_a, fut_b, fut_c).await;

// With outcomes
let outcomes: (Outcome<A, E>, Outcome<B, E>, Outcome<C, E>) = join\!(fut_a, fut_b, fut_c).await;
```

## Key Properties

### 1. All Complete
Every future runs to completion. Unlike try_join, join waits for all even if some fail.

### 2. Outcome Aggregation
If we need a single Outcome from join:
- Ok if ALL are Ok
- Err if ANY is Err (collect errors)
- Cancelled if ANY is Cancelled (highest severity wins)
- Panicked if ANY panicked (highest severity wins)

```rust
fn aggregate_outcomes<T>(outcomes: Vec<Outcome<T, E>>) -> Outcome<Vec<T>, Vec<E>> {
    // Severity lattice: worst outcome wins
    let worst_severity = outcomes.iter()
        .map(|o| o.severity())
        .max()
        .unwrap_or(Severity::Ok);

    match worst_severity {
        Severity::Ok => Outcome::Ok(outcomes.into_iter().map(|o| o.unwrap_ok()).collect()),
        Severity::Err => // collect all errors
        Severity::Cancelled => // return Cancelled with reason
        Severity::Panicked => // return Panicked
    }
}
```

### 3. Cancellation Propagation
If the parent region is cancelled:
- Cancellation propagates to all futures
- All futures drain according to their budgets
- join completes with Cancelled outcome

### 4. Fair Polling
All futures get polled fairly:
```rust
// Round-robin polling
loop {
    for i in 0..futures.len() {
        if \!completed[i] {
            match futures[i].poll(cx) {
                Poll::Ready(outcome) => {
                    completed[i] = true;
                    results[i] = Some(outcome);
                }
                Poll::Pending => {}
            }
        }
    }
    if completed.iter().all(|&c| c) {
        break;
    }
    yield_now().await;
}
```

## Implementation

### Macro Expansion
```rust
join\!(a, b, c)
// Expands to:
{
    let __join = Join3::new(a, b, c);
    __join.await
}
```

### Join Future
```rust
pub struct Join2<F1, F2> {
    fut1: MaybeDone<F1>,
    fut2: MaybeDone<F2>,
}

enum MaybeDone<F: Future> {
    Pending(F),
    Done(F::Output),
    Gone,
}

impl<F1, F2> Future for Join2<F1, F2>
where
    F1: Future,
    F2: Future,
{
    type Output = (F1::Output, F2::Output);

    fn poll(self: Pin<&mut Self>, cx: &mut Context<'_>) -> Poll<Self::Output> {
        let this = self.project();

        let done1 = this.fut1.poll(cx);
        let done2 = this.fut2.poll(cx);

        if done1 && done2 {
            Poll::Ready((this.fut1.take(), this.fut2.take()))
        } else {
            Poll::Pending
        }
    }
}
```

### Variadic Generation
Use proc-macro to generate Join2, Join3, ... JoinN for N up to 16.

## Macro Syntax

```rust
// Named fields (useful for documentation)
join\! {
    user = fetch_user(id),
    posts = fetch_posts(id),
    comments = fetch_comments(id),
}
// Returns: JoinResult { user, posts, comments }

// Tuple syntax
join\!(fut1, fut2, fut3)
// Returns: (O1, O2, O3)
```

## Integration Points

- Cx propagated to all branches
- Budget split/shared across branches
- Obligations tracked per-branch

## Testing

- Basic join of 2, 3, N futures
- Join with mixed success/failure
- Join under cancellation
- Join with panicking future
- Polling fairness
- Type inference works

## Acceptance Criteria

- [ ] join\! macro for 2-16 futures
- [ ] JoinN future structs
- [ ] MaybeDone wrapper
- [ ] Outcome aggregation
- [ ] Cancellation propagation
- [ ] Fair polling
- [ ] Named field syntax
